{{Orphan|date=January 2017}}
In mathematics, the '''hafnian''' of an [[adjacency matrix]] of a graph is the number of [[Matching (graph theory)#Definition|perfect matchings]] in the graph. It was so named by [[Eduardo R. Caianiello]] "to mark the fruitful period of stay in [[Copenhagen]] (Hafnia in Latin)."<ref>F. Guerra, in ''Imagination and Rigor: Essays on Eduardo R. Caianiello's Scientific Heritage'', edited by Settimo Termini, Springer Science & Business Media, 2006, page 98</ref>
The hafnian of a 2n&nbsp;×&nbsp;2n symmetric matrix is computed as
: <math> \operatorname{haf}(A) = \frac{1}{n!2^n} \sum_{\sigma \in S_{2n}} \prod_{j=1}^n A_{\sigma(2j - 1), \sigma(2j)}, </math>
where <math>S_{2n}</math> is the [[symmetric group]] on [''2n''].<ref>Rudelson, Mark, Alex Samorodnitsky, and Ofer Zeitouni. "Random Gaussian matrices and Hafnian estimators." ''arXiv preprint arXiv:1409.3905'' (2014). [[arxiv:1409.3905|http://arxiv.org/abs/1409.3905]]</ref>
Equivalently, : <math> \operatorname{haf}(A) = \sum_{M \in \mathcal{M}} \prod_{\scriptscriptstyle (u, v) \in M} A_{u, v} </math> where <math>\mathcal{M}</math> is the set of all 1-factors ([[perfect matching]]s) on the complete graph <math>K_{2n}</math>, namely the set of all <math>(2n)!/(n!2^n)</math> ways to partition the set <math>\{1, 2, \dots, 2n\}</math> into <math>n</math> subsets of size <math>2</math>.<ref>{{cite book | title=Combinatorics and Complexity of Partition Functions | page=93 | author=Alexander Barvinok | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9LlZDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA93}}</ref><ref>{{cite arxiv | page=7 | authors=Alexander Barvinok, Guus Regts | title=Weighted counting of integer points in a subspace | eprint = 1706.05423}}</ref>
