[[File:Lou van den dries.jpg|thumb|Lou van den Dries, [[Mathematical Research Institute of Oberwolfach|Oberwolfach]], 1988]]
'''Laurentius Petrus Dignus "Lou" van den Dries''' (born May 26, 1951) is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[mathematician]] working in [[model theory]]. He is a professor of mathematics at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]].

He completed his PhD at [[Utrecht University]] in 1978 under the supervision of [[Dirk van Dalen]] with a dissertation entitled ''Model Theory of Fields''.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=4836|title=Lou van den Dries}}</ref>

Van den Dries is most known for his seminal work in [[o-minimality]]. He has also made contributions to the model theory of [[P-adic number|{{mvar|p}}-adic fields]], [[valuation (algebra)|valued fields]], and [[finite fields]], and to the study of [[transseries]]. With [[Alex Wilkie]], he improved [[Gromov's theorem on groups of polynomial growth]] using [[nonstandard analysis|nonstandard methods]].

Van den Dries has been a corresponding member of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]] since 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/correspondents/4054|title=L.P.D. van den Dries|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=[[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=September 4, 2017}}</ref> He was an invited speaker at the 1990 [[International Congress of Mathematicians]] in [[Kyoto]] and delivered the [[Tarski Lectures]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mathunion.org/db/ICM/Speakers/SortedByLastname.php|title=ICM Plenary and Invited Speakers since 1897|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=[[International Mathematical Union]]|access-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://math.berkeley.edu/about/events/lectures/tarski|title=The Tarski Lectures|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=Department of Mathematics at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]|access-date=September 5, 2017}}</ref> He was awarded the Shoenfield Prize from the [[Association for Symbolic Logic]] in 2016 for his chapter "Lectures on the Model Theory of Valued Fields" in ''Model Theory in Algebra, Analysis and Arithmetic'', edited by [[Dugald Macpherson]] and Carlo Toffalori.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aslonline.org/Shoenfield_recipients.html|title=Shoenfield Prize Recipients|author=<!--Not stated-->|publisher=[[Association for Symbolic Logic]]|access-date=September 8, 2017}}</ref> Van den Dries was jointly awarded the 2018 [[Karp Prize]] with [[Matthias Aschenbrenner]] and Joris van der Hoeven "for their work in model theory, especially on asymptotic differential algebra and the model theory of transseries."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aslonline.org/files/newsletters/pdfs/April2018newsletter.pdf|title=ASL Newsletter|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=April 2018|publisher=[[Association for Symbolic Logic]]|access-date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>

His doctoral students include [[Matthias Aschenbrenner]].

